{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Hopkins syndrome | synonym = | image = | width = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | field = <!-- from Wikidata, can be overwritten --> | symptoms = | onset = | duration = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | frequency = | deaths = }}
'''Hopkins syndrome''' is a [[neurological disorder]]. Its cause has not been established, but its association with asthma exacerbations (usually with a respiratory infection as a trigger) has led to suspicion that the initial viral insult that causes the respiratory infection is also implicated in the subsequent paralysis. [[Herpes simplex virus]] type I DNA has been found in the [[cerebrospinal fluid]] of at least one patient diagnosed with Hopkins syndrome.<ref name=Kyllerman>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0887-8994(93)90091-P | last1 = Kyllerman | first1 = MG | last2 = Herner | first2 = S | last3 = Bergström | first3 = TB | last4 = Ekholm | first4 = SE | title = PCR diagnosis of primary herpesvirus type I in poliomyelitis-like paralysis and respiratory tract disease | journal = Pediatric neurology | volume = 9 | issue = 3 | pages = 227–9 | year = 1993 | pmid = 8394714 }}</ref> In several cases, anti-viral antibody titers for [[echovirus]], [[enterovirus]], [[coxsackievirus]] and [[poliovirus]] types 1, 2 and 3 were specifically sought; all were negative.<ref name=Okayama>{{cite journal | last1 = Okayama | first1 = A | last2 = Hara | first2 = H | last3 = Shigeto | first3 = H | last4 = Yamada | first4 = T | last5 = Kira | first5 = J | title = A case of Hopkins syndrome with onset at puberty | journal = [[Rinsho Shinkeigaku]] | volume = 39 | issue = 4 | pages = 452–5 | year = 1999 | pmid = 10391972 }}</ref><sup>,</sup><ref name=Kurokawa>{{cite journal | last1 = Kurokawa | first1 = T | last2 = Taniwaki | first2 = T | last3 = Arakawa | first3 = K | last4 = Yamada | first4 = T | last5 = Kira | first5 = J | title = An adult case of recurrent myelopathy presenting with monoplegia following asthmatic attacks | journal = Fukuoka igaku zasshi = Hukuoka acta medica | volume = 91 | issue = 3 | pages = 85–9 | year = 2000 | pmid = 10826222 }}</ref> There is one reported case in which ''[[Mycoplasma pneumoniae]]'' infection was found in the patient.<ref name=Acharya>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0887-8994(96)00248-2 | last1 = Acharya | first1 = AB | last2 = Lakhani | first2 = PK | title = Hopkins syndrome associated with Mycoplasma infection | journal = Pediatric neurology | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | pages = 54–5 | year = 1997 | pmid = 9044403 }}</ref>
The syndrome appears to involve the [[spinal cord]]: specifically, the [[Anterior horn of spinal cord|anterior horn cells]] subserving the affected muscles are often damaged. The evidence for anterior horn cell involvement comes from [[Radiology|radiological]] <ref name="Kurokawa"/><sup>,</sup><ref name=Nakano>{{cite journal | last1 = Nakano | first1 = Y | last2 = Kohira | first2 = R | last3 = Yamazaki | first3 = H | last4 = Fujita | first4 = N | last5 = Fuchigami | first5 = T | last6 = Okubo | first6 = O | last7 = Harada | first7 = K | title = Hopkins syndrome: oral prednisolone was effective for the paralysis | journal = No to hattatsu. Brain and development | volume = 33 | issue = 1 | pages = 69–73 | year = 2001 | pmid = 11197900 }}</ref><sup>,</sup><ref name=Arita>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0887-8994(95)00181-E | last1 = Arita | first1 = J | last2 = Nakae | first2 = Y | last3 = Matsushima | first3 = H | last4 = Maekawa | first4 = K | title = Hopkins syndrome: T2-weighted high intensity of anterior horn on spinal MR imaging | journal = Pediatric neurology | volume = 13 | issue = 3 | pages = 263–5 | year = 1995 | pmid = 8554668 }}</ref> and [[electromyograph]]ical studies.<ref name="Acharya"/> In one case, a [[biopsy]] of an affected muscle "revealed scattered atrophic fibers, indicating lesions in the anterior horn cells of the spinal cord".<ref name=Mizuno>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0387-7604(94)00125-H | last1 = Mizuno | first1 = Y | last2 = Komori | first2 = S | last3 = Shigetomo | first3 = R | last4 = Kurihara | first4 = E | last5 = Tamagawa | first5 = K | last6 = Komiya | first6 = K | title = Poliomyelitis-like illness after acute asthma (Hopkins syndrome): a histological study of biopsied muscle in a case | journal = Brain & development | volume = 17 | issue = 2 | pages = 126–9 | year = 1995 | pmid = 7625547 }}</ref>
As the illness is rare, no treatments have been subjected to a [[randomized controlled trial]]. [[Acyclovir]],<ref name="Kyllerman"/> [[steroid]]s and therapeutic [[plasma exchange]] have been tried; one report suggests that the latter is more effective than steroidal therapy.<ref name=Kira>{{cite journal | last1 = Kira | first1 = J | title = Neural damage associated with allergic diseases: pathomechanism and therapy | journal = [[Rinsho Shinkeigaku]] | volume = 43 | issue = 11 | pages = 756–60 | year = 2003 | pmid = 15152457 }}</ref> The prognosis for recovery of function of the affected limbs is generally considered to be poor.
