{{Infobox scientist | name = Kosali Ilayperuma Simon | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Sri Lanka]] | birth_name = Kosali Ilayperuma | death_date = | death_place = | spouse = Daniel Simon | children = 6 | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | alma_mater = [[Hamilton College (New York)|Hamilton College]], [[University of Maryland]] | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | known_for = | author_abbrev_bot = | influenced = | signature = | website = https://spea.indiana.edu/faculty-research/directory/profiles/faculty/full-time/simon-kosali.html | footnotes = | ethnicity = | field = Economics | work_institutions = [[Indiana University]], [[Cornell University]], [[Michigan State University]] | prizes = | religion = }}
'''Kosali Ilayperuma Simon''' is the Herman B Wells Endowed Professor in [[health economics]] at School of Public and Environmental Affairs (SPEA) at [[Indiana University]] which she joined in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://spea.indiana.edu/faculty-research/directory/profiles/faculty/full-time/simon-kosali.html |title= Kosali Simon Indiana page |accessdate= 26 March 2017}}</ref>
== Academic career ==
She graduated with a bachelor's in [[economics]] and [[German Literature]] from [[Hamilton College (New York)|Hamilton College]] in 1994. After a year studying in Europe as a [[Thomas_J._Watson_Fellowship|Watson Fellow]], she obtained a [[doctorate degree]] in economics from [[University of Maryland, College Park]] in 1999.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.iu.edu/stories/2017/08/iub/inside/25-kosali-simon.html|title=For Wells Professor, a busy life is a fulfilling life|last=Hinnefeld|first=Steve|work=News at IU|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en-US}}</ref>
She is a research associate at the [[NBER]], affiliated with the Children, Health Care, and Health Economics programs,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nber.org/people/kosali_simon|title=Kosali I. Simon|website=www.nber.org|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref> and an associate editor of the Journal of Health Economics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-health-economics/editorial-board |title= Journal of Health Economics - Editorial Board |accessdate= 6 October 2018}}</ref>She is consulted by the press as an expert in the field of health care economics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianapublicmedia.org/news/experts-weigh-hip-20s-fate-proposed-gop-aca-replacement-115578|title=Experts Weigh HIP 2.0’s Fate Under Proposed GOP ACA Replacement|work=News - Indiana Public Media|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2016/12/medicaid-and-mike-pence/511262|title=Indiana’s Medicaid Experiment May Reveal Obamacare’s Future|last=Semuels|first=Alana|date=2016-12-21|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-11-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.marketplace.org/2016/01/06/health-care/effect-obamacare-employment|title=The effect of Obamacare on employment|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref>
Recently, some of her work has focused on the impact of the [[Affordable Care Act]] on the labour market regarding work hours; she finds very minimal effect on part-time work as a result of the institution of the law.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.healthaffairs.org/content/35/1/119.short |title= Moriya, A.S., Selden, T.M. and Simon, K.I., 2016. Little Change Seen In Part-Time Employment As A Result Of The Affordable Care Act. Health affairs, 35(1), pp.119-123. |accessdate= 26 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.healthaffairs.org/content/35/1/111.short |title= Gooptu, A., Moriya, A.S., Simon, K.I. and Sommers, B.D., 2016. Medicaid expansion did not result in significant employment changes or job reductions in 2014. Health affairs, 35(1), pp.111-118. |accessdate= 26 March 2017}}</ref>
